<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="396" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,577,962]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,793,818]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Remarks.</emphasis>
The genus was erected by 
<bibRefCitation box="[644,792,793,818]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" refId="ref5533" refString="Hyatt, K. H. (1954) The African spiders of the family Ctenidae in the collections of the British Museum (Natural History). Annals and Magazine of Natural History, 7, 877 - 894. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222935408651809" type="journal article">Hyatt (1954)</bibRefCitation>
for 11 ctenid spiders from Africa as a member of the subfamily Acantheinae 
<bibRefCitation box="[425,572,829,854]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" refId="ref5983" refString="Simon, E. (1897) Materiaux pour servir a la faune arachnologique de l'Asie meridionale. V. Arachnides recueillis a Dehra-Dun (N. W. Prov.) et dans le Dekkan par M. A. Smythies. Memoires de la Societe Zoologique de France, 10, 252 - 262." type="journal article">Simon, 1897</bibRefCitation>
and was later transferred to Cteninae 
<bibRefCitation box="[1025,1172,829,854]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" refId="ref5983" refString="Simon, E. (1897) Materiaux pour servir a la faune arachnologique de l'Asie meridionale. V. Arachnides recueillis a Dehra-Dun (N. W. Prov.) et dans le Dekkan par M. A. Smythies. Memoires de la Societe Zoologique de France, 10, 252 - 262." type="journal article">Simon, 1897</bibRefCitation>
(
<bibRefCitation pageId="1" pageNumber="396" refId="ref5686" refString="Polotow, D. &amp; Brescovit, A. D. (2014) Phylogenetic analysis of the tropical wolf spider subfamily Cteninae (Arachnida, Araneae, Ctenidae). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 170, 333 - 361. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / Zoj. 12101" type="journal article">Polotow &amp; Brescovit 2014</bibRefCitation>
). To date, the genus has 20 nominal species, three are known only from males, eight only from females, whereas nine are known from both sexes (World Spider Catalog 2017). The genus is currently restricted to Africa (World Spider Catalog 2017).
</paragraph>
